    <!-- FAQ SECTION -->
    <h2 id="faq">Frequently Asked Questions About Collagen Gummies for Joints</h2>

    <details class="fq"><summary>What type of collagen is best for joints?</summary><p>Type II collagen is most important for joints — it constitutes 60% of cartilage protein. UC-II at 40mg daily was shown to be twice as effective as glucosamine + chondroitin in a 2016 RCT. Hydrolyzed collagen peptides (types I, II, III at 5g) also support cartilage maintenance through amino acid supply.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How long does collagen take to help joints?</summary><p>Joint benefits typically require 8-12 weeks of consistent daily use. Cartilage is avascular tissue that repairs slowly. A 2017 study in athletes showed significant pain reduction after 12 weeks at 5g daily. Do not expect noticeable improvement in the first 4 weeks.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can collagen gummies rebuild cartilage?</summary><p>Collagen supplements support cartilage maintenance and slow degradation, but do not directly rebuild lost cartilage. UC-II reduces immune-mediated cartilage breakdown. Hydrolyzed peptides provide amino acids for cartilage repair. For advanced osteoarthritis, supplementation alone is insufficient.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Is UC-II better than hydrolyzed collagen for joints?</summary><p>They work through different mechanisms. UC-II modulates immune response to reduce cartilage degradation. Hydrolyzed collagen provides amino acid building blocks. UC-II is better for inflammatory joint conditions. Hydrolyzed collagen is better for activity-related wear. Ideally, use both.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>How much collagen should I take for joint health?</summary><p>For UC-II: 40mg daily on an empty stomach. For hydrolyzed peptides: 5-10g daily. Most gummies provide 2.5-5g per serving. For therapeutic joint support, 5g minimum. For general maintenance, 2.5g may suffice.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Do collagen gummies work as well as powder for joints?</summary><p>Yes, when matched for dose. Powders typically provide 10-20g; gummies provide 2.5-5g. For joint maintenance at 5g, gummies are equally effective. For higher therapeutic doses, powder may be more practical.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Can I take collagen gummies with glucosamine?</summary><p>Yes. They work through complementary pathways: collagen rebuilds the protein framework, glucosamine fills in cushioning material. No adverse interactions documented. You can continue glucosamine while adding collagen.</p></details>
    <details class="fq"><summary>Are collagen gummies safe for long-term use?</summary><p>Yes. Collagen is a natural protein constituting 30% of all protein in the human body. No adverse effects have been documented in clinical trials lasting up to 24 weeks. Long-term use is recommended for sustained joint benefit.</p></details>

